        "Answer: \n\n**Patient Summary**\nThis 67-year-old male with a history of ESRD on hemodialysis, Type 2 DM, HTN, and CAD was initially admitted for chest pain, productive cough, and night sweats to rule out myocardial infarction (MI) and active tuberculosis (TB). Serial troponins remained flat (0.04-0.05 ng/mL) and triple sputum AFB smears were negative, ruling out MI and active TB. On the second day of hospitalization, the patient experienced sudden left-sided flaccid paralysis and expressive aphasia while undergoing hemodialysis. A 'Code Stroke' was called; CT brain perfusion showed an acute right MCA territory ischemia (penumbra). He received intravenous tPA with significant clinical improvement. Follow-up MRI confirmed an acute infarct in the right posterior frontal lobe. Transthoracic echocardiography (TTE) with a bubble study was negative for a patent foramen ovale or atrial septal defect. Hypertension was aggressively managed, and he was started on high-dose Aspirin and Atorvastatin for secondary stroke prevention. At discharge, his motor deficits had mostly resolved, though mild expressive aphasia/dysarthria persisted.\n\n**Past Medical History**\n- End-Stage Renal Disease (ESRD) on hemodialysis (Stage 5 CKD).\n- Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus (DM2).\n- Coronary Artery Disease (CAD) s/p drug-eluting stent (DES).\n- Hypertension (HTN).\n- Hyperlipidemia.\n- Latent TB (previously treated with INH).\n- Chronic Headaches.\n- Anemia.\n\n**Discharge Medications**\n1. Aspirin: 325 mg PO DAILY\n2. Atorvastatin: 80 mg PO DAILY\n3. Carvedilol: 25 mg (12.5 mg x 2 tabs) PO BID\n4. Lisinopril: 20 mg PO BID\n5. Sevelamer carbonate (Renvela): 800 mg PO TID with meals\n6. B complex-vitamin C-folic acid: 1 capsule PO DAILY\n7. Megace Oral Suspension: 600 mg (15 mL) PO DAILY\n8. Tramadol: 50 mg PO Q6H as needed for headache\n9. Lidocaine 4% Cream: Topical as needed prior to dialysis\n\n**Physical Examination**\n- **General:** Awake, alert, and interactive; mental status clea