        "The patient is a 67-year-old male who was admitted for chest pain, pulmonary edema, and to rule out tuberculosis (TB) given a history of cough and night sweats. During his hospitalization, specifically while undergoing hemodialysis, the patient developed acute left-sided flaccid paralysis and aphasia. A \"Code Stroke\" was initiated, and diagnostic imaging including CT brain perfusion revealed a right middle cerebral artery (MCA) territory perfusion defect with penumbra. He was promptly treated with intravenous tPA, which led to a significant improvement in motor function, although mild left-sided facial droop and expressive aphasia persisted at the time of transfer from the ICU.\n\nImaging studies confirmed an acute ischemic event and identified underlying vascular risks. Head MRI showed an acute infarct in the right posterior frontal lobe involving the precentral gyrus, along with chronic small vessel ischemic changes. CT angiography revealed atherosclerotic disease with at least 65% diameter stenosis of the left proximal internal carotid artery (ICA), though the right MCA and ICA terminus appeared unremarkable. A transthoracic echocardiogram (TTE) showed a left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) greater than 55% with no evidence of an atrial septal defect or patent foramen ovale during a bubble study, suggesting a low immediate risk for a cardiogenic embolic source.\n\nSignificant laboratory monitoring during the stay showed a hemoglobin range of 10.6-12.2 g/dL and creatinine levels between 5.9 and 10.9 mg/dL, which are consistent with his baseline end-stage renal disease (ESRD). Myocardial infarction was ruled out by stable cardiac biomarkers, with troponin T levels remaining flat between 0.04 and 0.05 ng/mL. Additionally, the patient was cleared of active tuberculosis after three consecutive negative sputum acid-fast bacilli (AFB) smears and negative concentrated smears. Pulmonary edema identified on initial chest X-rays was attributed to fluid overload and successfully resolved following dialysis and medical management.\n\nAt the time of discharge, the patient's condition was stable; he was ambulatory with assistance and demonstrated motor strength of 4+/5 bilaterally. His medication regimen was optimized for secondary stroke prevention and blood pressure management, including high-dose atorvastatin (80 mg), aspirin (325 mg), lisinopril, and carvedilol. Outpatient follow-up was arranged with neurology for continued deficit monitoring, cardiology for a scheduled transesophageal echocardiogram (TEE), and primary care for general management. He was also referred for outpatient physical, occupational, and speech therapy to address lingering neurological deficits.": "95% Bootstrap Confidence Interval: (0.0%, 0.0%), Median: 0.0%"
